Network Routing 4/7 - essential for internet functionality 

? What is routing - the process of figuring out which path your data/ requests take to travel across a network 

? Important - makes sure that data/requests reach the right place/destination quickly & efficiently 

? How routing works - Routers (hardware) determines which path the data should take and the  routing table  is list of directions that says if you want to get “here” take this route 

Computer 1 -> router ( checks routing table ) -> jumps thru network - > computer 2 


? Why routing important in DEVOPS - 

: good route ensures data packets - take most efficient path = reduced latancy + net perform
: ensures reliable application delivery 
: crucial for managing complex infrastructure


? Types of routing -

Static routing = set up the routes manually + stay the same and don’t change ( directions ) ( old school map )
- Manually configured 
- Fixed oath by network admin 
- Simple but not scalable for larger networks ( headache manually ) 

Dynamic routing = Routes update in real time so the network can figure out the best route ( directions ) ( gps)
- Automatically adjusts routes - even if there are problems ( ex. more traffic on a path on the network )
- Uses Routing protocols to find best path for data 
- Scalable and adaptable - suitable for large and changing networking seamlessly 


? What are routing protocols -  [algorithms / Sets of rules] for routers 2 router communication to figure out the best path for traffic / data 

- Automate route updates
- Enhance network efficiency = improve latency , reduce congestion/ traffic 

? Examples of routing protocols 

OSPF = open shortest path first -  single organisation network - ( internal gps for shortest path in network ) 

BGP = Border gateway protocol - big networks talk to different organisations - make sure data/traffic routed effiencetly between these different location son the internet  ( for big distributed environments  ) 
